			"contents": "# Resume Versions\n\n1 = Master resume (include everything)\n2 = Technical only (include only tech skills, no call center stuff)\n3 = Customer-facing only (for sales & call center)\n\n# Why did I leave companies?\n\n- Day Trading - well, I don't do it anymore... I'm looking for something with less risk -- less overhead.\n- Vighty - even though we had a killer app, I talked with an executive at Youngevity. He said they weren't comfortable with it because it was using a webscraper (which I totally understood) - so we made the decision to shut it down and move on.\n- Youngevity - eventually our arrangements with TV advertising fizzled out and our lead streams with them.\n- Delta Institute - I left to try my hand at owning my own businesses.\n- AQPWR - I left for the same reason everyone else left - they stopped paying us.\n    - They made a business decision to focus on big money deals, instead of selling to smaller consumers.\n- Rising Artist Studios - I got married and was offered a job at AQPWR\n\n# Skills Review\n\nSome key files in your past history may provide powerful reminders of what you are capable of.\n\n## DownlineToolbox\n\nRuby ERB\n`C:\\mikes_data\\ARCHIVE - BIZ\\RETIRED - BUSINESS - Vighty\\DownlineToolbox\\Backups\\downlinetoolbox\\app\\views\\ygy_positions\\semd_report.html.erb`\nmain takeaways: html.erb files are a mix between html and ruby. <html><%= content_tag_for(:tr, @users) do |user| %></html>\n`C:\\mikes_data\\ARCHIVE - BIZ\\RETIRED - BUSINESS - Vighty\\DownlineToolbox\\Backups\\downlinetoolbox\\app\\models\\ygy_position.rb`\nmain takeaways: this file is where the magic happened. It's the main class that generated the downlinetoolbox reports including crawling, manipulating the csv files, etc...\n\n## DownlineNinja (frmrly TheMagnum)\n\n`C:\\mikes_data\\ARCHIVE - BIZ\\BIZ - Youngevity\\QWiz\\Downline_Ninja\\downlineNinja\\Classes\\`\nThis folder contains the Scraper as well as the Quals class which spun up the spreadsheet using SpreadsheetGear and the Validator to make sure they were subscribed. Also, it contains the YGYq spreadsheet itself.\n\n`C:\\mikes_data\\ARCHIVE - BIZ\\BIZ - Youngevity\\QWiz` - contains the earliest iterations of TheMagnum spreadsheets. contains VBA which accessed outlook to mass-send emails based on screenshots from excel, primed the data to copy and paste it down\n\n## Youngevity ygy_rotator javascript\n\n`C:\\mikes_data\\Dropbox\\Scripts\\ygy_rotate.js` - basically, it choosed randomly from a list and the alters web elements\n\n## Google script for altering spreadsheet and putting items at the top\n\n`C:\\mikes_data\\Dropbox\\Scripts\\WallachRevolutionLeads Sort.gs` - sorts a list of google sheets leads and puts the newest ones at the top\n\nin google drive under: Archive\\90 Worldwide\\90 Worldwide\\Leads - wallachrevolutionleads - contains the google script which auto-sorts the leads file\n\n\n\nEntertainment\nGloria's Little Italy - Apr 2008 - Jun 2008\nProvo, UT\n\nPerformed on the weekends, both Friday and Saturday, for three hours each night.  Created a musical portfolio of nearly a hundreds songs during this time to minimize repetition and maximize entertainment value.\n\n# Rules of Resume writing\n\n# Writing a killer resume\n\nuse action verbs: https://www.indeed.com/career-advice/interviewing/action-verbs-to-make-your-resume-stand-out?from=careeradvice-US\n6 universal rules: https://www.indeed.com/career-advice/resumes-cover-letters/6-universal-rules-for-resume-writing?from=career_guide_resume_drip_jsx_for_cg_us_template_1_of_6_v1&utm_campaign=jsx_for_cg&utm_source=career_guide_resume_drip_jsx_for_cg_us_template_1_of_6_v1&utm_medium=email\n4 commons resume mistakes: https://idealistcareers.org/common-resume-mistakes/\nSkill proficiencies: https://business.tutsplus.com/tutorials/how-to-list-skills-on-a-resume--cms-28652\n    Beginner. You can handle the basic features of the program, but you can’t do complicated tricks or troubleshoot problems yet.\n    Intermediate. You can also troubleshoot and do some fancy tricks. But you might need to Google some functions or ask in forums from time to time.\n    Proficient. You’re not yet an expert, but you can handle advanced functions and troubleshoot problems by examining things on your own. You don’t need a manual.\n    Expert. You know the program like the back of your hand. You know of obscure features, tricks, and weird problems, so much so that other people often come to you for help.\ntop 10 skills to add to resume: https://www.indeed.com/career-advice/resumes-cover-letters/best-resume-skills\n**indeed full career guide**: https://www.indeed.com/career-advice\nsix rules: https://www.indeed.com/career-advice/resumes-cover-letters/6-universal-rules-for-resume-writing?from=career_guide_resume_drip_jsx_for_cg_us_template_1_of_6_v1&utm_campaign=jsx_for_cg&utm_source=career_guide_resume_drip_jsx_for_cg_us_template_1_of_6_v1&utm_medium=email\nResume Critique: https://www.topresume.com/?action=resumecritiqueview&at=bDDTibodr7vTzRQ8Bmq7ANlpIA4k4awI&rs=&utm_medium=email&utm_source=critique-funnel&utm_content=cr_html&utm_campaign=cr_html\nCover Letter Starting Techniques: https://www.indeed.com/career-advice/resumes-cover-letters/powerful-ways-to-start-a-cover-letter?from=career_guide_resume_drip_jsx_for_cg_us_template_4_of_6_v1&utm_campaign=jsx_for_cg&utm_source=career_guide_resume_drip_jsx_for_cg_us_template_4_of_6_v1&utm_medium=email\n",
